the Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">A popular, fast-paced trade has boosted the options market to record =
volumes in recent years. Now, Wall Street is looking to push it even furthe=
r.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Zero-day-to-expiry options let investors=
 bet on whether a particular stock-market index will rise or fall by the en=
d of the day. They have drawn an enthusiastic following among amateur inves=
tors, even as skeptics call them a form of gambling. They are sometimes kno=
wn by the hashtag #0dte.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So far, the #0dte =
boom has been limited to options tied to indexes such as the S&amp;P 500 or=
 Nasdaq-100. The next frontier could be options on stocks such as Tesla or =
Nvidia. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Michael McCaskill, a 48-y=
ear-old day trader and volleyball-programs coordinator in Louisville, Ky., =
trades short-dated options in hopes of hitting the jackpot. He=E2=80=99s in=
trigued by the prospect of more-frequent expirations on single-stock option=
s.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe pe=
rcentage gains are incredible,=E2=80=9D said McCaskill, who has previously =
made profitable bets on GameStop, Netflix and PayPal. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s=
 the short-dated options that give you that, whether it=E2=80=99s weekly or=
 daily.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am sorry, I=
 am sure he has lots of profitable trades and I don=E2=80=99t mean to be ru=
de, but just, statistically speaking,=C2=A0for equity market makers, there =
are few more beautiful phrases in the English language than =E2=80=9Cday tr=
ader and volleyball-programs coordinator.=E2=80=9D If you walk into the off=
ices of Susquehanna International Group and say =E2=80=9Chi I am a day trad=
er and volleyball-programs coordinator from Louisville, Ky., and I love sho=
rt-dated options but I wish they were shorter-dated, can you help,=E2=80=9D=
 they will treat you like a celebrity and give you anything you=C2=A0ask fo=
r. You are their muse.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As it happens, Susqu=
ehanna is salivating over single-stock 0dtes but Robinhood, less so:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In closed-door industry meetings, ret=
ail brokerages such as Robinhood Markets, Schwab, Tastytrade and Morgan Sta=
nley=E2=80=99s E*Trade have advocated for a cautious approach, concerned th=
ey could face a customer backlash if investors=E2=80=99 options trades blow=
 up, the people said.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other firms=E2=
=80=94including Susquehanna International Group, a huge options-market make=
r, and Nasdaq=E2=80=94have actively promoted bringing daily expirations to =
single-stock options, the people said. Both market makers and exchanges sta=
nd to benefit from the volumes that could come from further growth in the #=
0dte phenomenon.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The retail br=
okers=C2=A0<em>basically=C2=A0</em>make money if their customers are happy;=
 the market makers=C2=A0<em>basically=C2=A0</em>make=C2=A0money by trading =
against them. There is an overlap in their interests, but it is not complet=
e. If Robinhood gives its customers new ways to lose money faster, that=E2=
=80=99s probably bad for Robinhood in the long term, but it=E2=80=99s very =
good for whoever is on the other side of those trades.</p><table class=3D"l=
